{"questionId":"17625","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The Maxwell Ohm Company is designing a portable Bluetooth speaker. The speaker is in the&nbsp;shape of a cylinder with a hemisphere at each end of the cylinder.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/dbcd221b4bb4d9c012b7a806f9934266848ede94.png\"></p>\n<p>The dimensions of the speaker, in centimetres, are illustrated in the following diagram where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi></math>&nbsp;is the radius of the hemisphere, and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>l</mi></math> is the length of the cylinder, with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>l</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>0</mn></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/d80c74eb2795a9d1751de44a78ed4859ee9616d8.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Write down an expression for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi></math>, the volume (cm<sup>3</sup>) of the speaker, in terms of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>l</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo></mrow></mfenced><mo> </mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mtext>π</mtext><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>l</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;(or equivalent)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em><em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em> for either the volume of a hemisphere formula multiplied by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> or the volume of a cylinder formula, and <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em> for completely correct expression. Accept equivalent expressions.&nbsp;Award at most <em><strong>(A1)(A0)</strong></em> if <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi></math> is used instead of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>l</mi></math>.</p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"17625","referenceCode":"19N.2.SL.TZ0.T_6a","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Write down an expression for V, the volume (cm3) of the speaker, in terms of r, l and π.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"a","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 5—Calculus","Topic 5—Calculus","SL 5.3—Differentiating polynomials, n E Z","Topic 5—Calculus","SL 5.6—Stationary points, local max and min","Topic 5—Calculus","SL 5.7—Optimisation","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.1—3d space, volume, angles, midpoints"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}